🔁 Sliding Window Technique – Introduction
The Sliding Window technique is an efficient algorithmic approach used to process a range of elements in an array or string by maintaining a “window” (subarray or substring) that moves step-by-step instead of recalculating results from scratch every time.
Instead of using nested loops to check all possible subarrays (which leads to higher time complexity like O(n²)), the sliding window optimizes the process by reusing previously computed results and adjusting only the necessary elements when the window shifts.
This makes it a powerful technique for solving problems involving contiguous subarrays or substrings.
💡 Core Idea
The main idea behind the sliding window is to:
-> Maintain a window with a start and end pointer
-> Expand the window when needed
-> Shrink the window when constraints are violated
-> Update the result dynamically while moving the window
This avoids redundant computations and improves performance significantly.
⚡ Why Use Sliding Window?
-> Reduces time complexity from O(n²) to O(n)
-> Efficient for large datasets
-> Eliminates unnecessary re-calculations
-> Commonly asked in coding interviews and DSA rounds
🧠 When to Use Sliding Window?
Use this technique when:
-> The problem involves contiguous subarrays or substrings
-> You are asked to find maximum, minimum, longest, or shortest window
-> The input is an array, string, or list
-> The problem includes conditions like sum, frequency, or length constraints
📌 Types of Sliding Window
1. Fixed Size Window
The window size remains constant while sliding across the array.
Example: Maximum sum of subarray of size k.
2. Variable Size Window
The window size expands and shrinks based on a condition.
Example: Longest substring without repeating characters.
🔍 General Working Pattern
1. Initialize two pointers (left and right)
2. Expand the right pointer to include elements into the window
3. Check if the window satisfies the condition
4. If not, move the left pointer to shrink the window
5. Update the result at each valid state
⏱️ Time Complexity
Usually O(n) because each element is visited at most twice (once by left pointer and once by right pointer)
🚀 Summary
The Sliding Window technique is a must-know pattern in Data Structures and Algorithms. 
It helps solve optimization problems on arrays and strings efficiently by converting brute-force solutions into linear-time solutions. 
Mastering this technique is essential for coding interviews, competitive programming, and real-world performance-critical applications.
